{"parentUuid":"c56e2a67-66ed-426f-9320-4460949ab931","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"9d031388-ff29-424a-b7c6-d9d67bb49acb","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a07f13fe1e20fdcfa","slug":"nifty-sleeping-flurry","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CXmhYsT1pShpEEnZR2zWkk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 782\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/782](https://www.erdosproblems.com/782)\n    23→\n    24→A question of Brown, Erdős, and Freedman [BEF90]. It is a classical fact that\n    25→the squares do not contain arithmetic progressions of length 4. An affirmative\n    26→answer to the first question implies an affirmative answer to the second.\n    27→\n    28→[BEF90] Brown, T. C., Erdős, P., and Freedman, A. R., _Quasi-progressions and\n    29→descending waves_. J. Combin. Theory Ser. A 53 (1990), no. 1, 81-95.\n    30→-/\n    31→\n    32→open Finset\n    33→\n    34→open scoped BigOperators\n    35→\n    36→namespace Erdos782\n    37→\n    38→/--\n    39→Erdős Problem 782, Part 1 (Quasi-progressions in the squares) [BEF90]:\n    40→\n    41→There exists a constant $C$ such that for any $k \\geq 2$, one can find $k$ perfect\n    42→squares $x_1 < x_2 < \\cdots < x_k$ forming a quasi-progression with gap $d$, meaning\n    43→$x_i + d \\leq x_{i+1} \\leq x_i + d + C$ for all consecutive pairs.\n    44→-/\n    45→@[category research open, AMS 5 11]\n    46→theorem erdos_782 : answer(sorry) ↔\n    47→    ∃ C : ℕ, ∀ k : ℕ, k ≥ 2 →\n    48→    ∃ (x : Fin k → ℕ) (d : ℕ), d > 0 ∧\n    49→    (∀ i, IsSquare (x i)) ∧\n    50→    (∀ i j : Fin k, i < j → x i < x j) ∧\n    51→    (∀ (i : ℕ) (hi : i + 1 < k),\n    52→      x ⟨i, by omega⟩ + d ≤ x ⟨i + 1, hi⟩ ∧\n    53→      x ⟨i + 1, hi⟩ ≤ x ⟨i, by omega⟩ + d + C) := by\n    54→  sorry\n    55→\n    56→/--\n    57→Erdős Problem 782, Part 2 (Combinatorial cubes in the squares) [BEF90]:\n    58→\n    59→For any $m$, the set of perfect squares contains a combinatorial cube of\n    60→dimension $m$: there exist $a$ and positive $b_1, \\ldots, b_m$ such that\n    61→$a + \\sum_{i \\in S} b_i$ is a perfect square for every subset\n    62→$S \\subseteq \\{1, \\ldots, m\\}$.\n    63→-/\n    64→@[category research open, AMS 5 11]\n    65→theorem erdos_782.variants.cubes : answer(sorry) ↔\n    66→    ∀ m : ℕ, ∃ (a : ℕ) (b : Fin m → ℕ),\n    67→    (∀ i, b i > 0) ∧\n    68→    (∀ S : Finset (Fin m), IsSquare (a + ∑ i ∈ S, b i)) := by\n    69→  sorry\n    70→\n    71→end Erdos782\n    72→"}]},"uuid":"48697c83-2826-4f7a-bf32-52bd6f7d6704","timestamp":"2026-03-11T00:52:50.036Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c56e2a67-66ed-426f-9320-4460949ab931"}
{"parentUuid":"48697c83-2826-4f7a-bf32-52bd6f7d6704","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"9d031388-ff29-424a-b7c6-d9d67bb49acb","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a07f13fe1e20fdcfa","slug":"nifty-sleeping-flurry","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01XgDEyiGGWLNRnd4v5P1Pp8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I found the Lean file for Erdos problem 782.\n\n## Result\n\n**File path:** `/home/ryan/formal-conjectures/FormalConjectures/ErdosProblems/782.lean`\n\n**File contents:**\n\nThe file contains two theorems related to Erdős Problem 782, which comes from a question by Brown, Erdős, and Freedman [BEF90]:\n\n1. **Part 1 (Quasi-progressions in the squares)**: States that there exists a constant C such that for any k ≥ 2, one can find k perfect squares forming a quasi-progression with gap d, where the difference between consecutive squares stays within [d, d+C].\n\n2. **Part 2 (Combinatorial cubes in the squares)**: States that for any m, the set of perfect squares contains a combinatorial cube of dimension m - there exist a and positive b₁, ..., bₘ such that a + Σ(i ∈ S) bᵢ is a perfect square for every subset S.\n\nBoth theorems are marked as open research problems with the status `answer(sorry)`, indicating that proofs are still needed. The reference points to https://www.erdosproblems.com/782 and the original BEF90 paper on quasi-progressions and descending waves."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1349,"cache_read_input_tokens":18495,"output_tokens":313,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1349},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYvNu1WgSNgQe53iF1wCU","type":"assistant","uuid":"95f436fa-